	   <a name=1016994631806></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f1016994631806><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=1016994631806>Brief Guide to Kiting</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=1016994631806#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73409><span id=Scholar>Mistress ancarett</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>107 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Mar 24th 1:33 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.54]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Kiting involves anywhere from 1 to 4 mobs being killed while they follow you. Important points: kiting should usually be done in relatively open areas of zones (so you can avoid additional mobs and avoid running into other players). Kiting should also be done with mobs of the same type (to avoid some catching up on you or some resisting spells). Four is the maximum for AoE effects to catch (hence the term quadkiting).<br><br>Start practice kiting one mob at a time in an open area until you get the feel for it. As a druid, you should start the kiting by using snare. You then run off a bit (while mob follows you) and either nuke or dot. Move off, keep hitting mob with spells (if it takes a while, recast snare!). Repeat until dead.<br><br>A nice variation on this for single mobs is to begin by snare/kiting and proceed to root it. Throw a few dots on and watch it die while you med. Fun eh?<br><br>To move up to multiple mob kiting, snare one mob, then, while it is chasing you, go after second of same type and so forth. Good luck!<br>&nbsp;<br>-- Ancarett, who lives at <a href="http://ancarett.com" target=_new>http://ancarett.com</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
